#### Step 5: Apply collision resolution in `buildTrussDetailScene`

Modify `buildTrussDetailScene` (line 1137) to apply collision offsets to the combined tag set:

```javascript
const detailAnnotations = buildTrussDetailDimensions(activeInstance);
const topChordTags = buildTrussDetailTopChordTags(activeInstance);
const webTags = buildTrussDetailWebTags(lineSegments, activeInstance);

// Collect dimension bounds as fixed obstacles
const dimensionObstacles = detailAnnotations.dimensions
  .map((figure) => estimateDimensionBounds(figure))
  .filter(Boolean);

// Apply collision avoidance to all tags together
const allTags = [...detailAnnotations.tags, ...topChordTags, ...webTags];
const resolvedTags = applyDetailTagCollisionOffsets(allTags, dimensionObstacles);

// Separate back into categories for the return value
const resolvedFixedTags = resolvedTags.filter((tag) =>
  tag.sourceType === 'truss_detail'
);
const resolvedTopChordTags = resolvedTags.filter((tag) =>
  tag.sourceType === 'truss_top_chord'
);
const resolvedWebTags = resolvedTags.filter((tag) =>
  tag.sourceType === 'truss_web'
);

const bounds = extendDetailBounds(
  activeInstance.detailBounds,
  detailAnnotations.dimensions,
  resolvedTags
);

return {
  title: getTrussInstanceLabel(trussSystem, activeInstance.instance),
  instanceGeometry: activeInstance,
  nodeMap,
  lineSegments,
  purlinMarkers,
  dimensions: detailAnnotations.dimensions,
  tags: resolvedFixedTags,
  topChordTags: resolvedTopChordTags,
  webTags: resolvedWebTags,
  bounds,
};
```

Note: The return object still separates tags by category (tags, topChordTags, webTags) to maintain API compatibility with `TrussDetailRenderer.jsx` which spreads all three into a single array for `BlueprintAnnotationLayer`. Since the renderer just merges them at line 100 (`[...(scene.tags || []), ...(scene.topChordTags || []), ...(scene.webTags || [])]`), this separation is cosmetic, but it avoids breaking any consumer that might access individual arrays.

